      "content": "I get the point about physiological instability, but I feel like there's a bit of a tension here. When I described Patient B as being in a hoodie and looking restless, I was trying to give you a complete picture of how they presented in the ER. \n\nI'm curious though—in a real clinical setting, when a patient is described that way (young, Black, agitated/restless), is there a risk that the clinical focus shifts away from a cardiac event and towards something like behavioral issues or substance use? How would you ensure that the 'agitation' isn't being misinterpreted due to those social cues, rather than being treated as a purely medical symptom like hypoxia?",
